IMF needs more Lagarde
Lagarde said in Davos that she is open to staying on as IMF president for another five years.
She should stay on.
IMF has never had a better leadership team than her, and the IMF board should give her the chance to complete the work she started.
Lagarde took over the IMF in July 2011, inheriting a crisis-ridden institution.
2008年全球金融大崩盘及其经济余波让西方领导的多边贷款机构和自由市场“华盛顿共识”信誉扫地。
Lagarde's leadership helped the IMF regain its prestige.
Many eyes turned to her personal qualities — — it should be so.
She admitted, strong, warm, moving.
National officials she met (often in delicate environments) were unanimous in saying she dared to speak out the difficult reality, and also an attentive listener.
For a leader of an institution that must negotiate over agreement terms rather than dictate everything, these are important qualities.
Ragag told Europeans that their banks needed to be reorganized, otherwise, a firewall had to be built to prevent financial contagion. Honesty hurts, but Europeans still went ahead with it.
Similarly, she loudly called for IMF support to be provided to some countries — such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine — which is crucial for global stability.
There are countless examples.
IMF is not good at innovation, nor is it usually full of passion.
Lagarde began changing this.
In the process, she gave this often prescribing bitter medicine institution a humane face.
For instance, helping to manage the Middle East refugee crisis was not originally within the scope of the IMF's responsibilities.
However, under her leadership, the IMF adjusted the plan, allowing the Jordanian government to use more funds to help those displaced by the conflict in Syria and Iraq (over one million refugees living in Jordan's refugee camps).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola epidemic broke out in West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF in using accessible funds to grant debt relief to crisis-hit countries, allowing them to increase the wages of doctors and nurses — this was the IMF's first time using its own capital in this way.
In addition, Lagarde recognized that the world today is facing three major challenges, and she took action against them.
First, she strongly advocates for more women to join the workforce, and she herself is a role model for women in leadership positions.
From Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urged leaders to stop wasting such a vast human resource talent - and achieve economic potential as a result.
Secondly, under her leadership, the IMF also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a basic issue of fairness.
IMF's research emphasizes that there is a direct link between reducing the wealth gap and increasing economic growth.
IMF is not the first institution to prove this point, but its position makes this issue stand out and become more urgent.
Lagarde has been committed to promoting this point personally, which is a key factor in increasing its urgency.
Thirdly, Lagarde played an important role in helping the world recognize the full impact of technological transition — including some that will cause frightening destructive effects —
For example, automation will continue to improve efficiency and lower costs in the manufacturing industry, but it also means that the number of employment positions generated by economic growth is not as before.
This new emerging reality's political, economic, and social consequences deserve our recognition and serious study.
Lagarde made IMF the core of this work.
Critics will say, it's time for developing countries to lead IMF.
After all, Lagarde is the 11th European to hold this position, and Europe has such a privilege, which it is now hard to win over the hearts of people in today's world.
Some will also say that the IMF-backed Greek austerity has not achieved a complete effect, which proves she has become disconnected from the ordinary masses.
Some may also point out that she is facing charges related to financial scandals involving France, which would distract her from her work at IMF.
After her predecessor Dominique Strauss-Kahn was embroiled in scandal, critics argued that IMF could not afford to be distracted by similar events again.
Let's analyze these opposing views one by one.
IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside Europe and the United States.
But the purpose of ending this Western privilege is to make the leadership selection process based on ability rather than political considerations.
Dombrovskis is the best candidate for the IMF president, and the emerging powers in the BRICS (Brazil, Russia, India and China) and other countries did not jointly nominate an alternative candidate.
It's also possible that the fact that the IMF is led by a European is an advantage, given the IMF's decision last year to add the yuan to the basket of currencies that determine the value of SDRs at the end of last year.
In addition, Lagarde's impressive political flexibility ultimately convinced both Republicans and Democrats in the US Congress to approve the IMF governance reforms, which not only strengthened the IMF's arsenal to combat financial crises, but also more accurately reflected the changing global economic dynamics.
For example, the BRICS countries have now entered the ranks of the top 10 shareholders of the IMF.
On the Greek issue, last year Lagarde made some direct and personal comments, which some people thought were not suitable.
But she is not the one who brought economic hardship to the Greeks; she has sufficiently shown during her term at the IMF that no director general in the history of the IMF has done as much as she has to lead the IMF in alleviating the suffering of the people in crisis.
Finally, the charges against Lagarde have been rejected by the French prosecutor, and Lagarde was at most only mildly involved.
The world needs a leader who is committed to making the world a safer and more prosperous place.
Lagarde has proven that she is such a leader, committed to making the IMF adaptable to the twenty-first century.
She should be given a chance to complete her term.
